 depending on the milieu.  The translocation is then essentially vertical if pedoclimatic conditions do  not produce superficial or subsuperficial (hypodermic) flowing ("lessivage").  "Lessivage", however, may appear in the whole profile, thus resulting in  the development of eluviated soil in situ. It may also occur only in the upper  part of the profile with a deposit in the subsurface horizons, which thus turn  into altero-illuvial (Boulet, 1978) or argillic B (FAO nomenclature, 1975)  horizons.  By contrast, when pedoclimatic conditions cause the destabilization of  surface horizons with an epidermic flowing, the plasma elements may be car-  ried away superficially in a lateral direction. That corresponds to a sort of  "selective erosion" (cf. Roose, 1980) which is now called "appauvrissement  de surface" or superficial impoverishment. Plasma is lost from surface hori-  zons whereas subsurface horizons are in fact B horizons of alteration.  (b) Any disjunction of clay--iron bonds within plasma will encourage  plasma-skeleton dissociation. Thus, plasma mobility will be increased, but  clay and iron will behave disjunctionally and may migrate separately.  The different cases mentioned can be observed together with iron segrega-  tion, leading to recrystallization of iron constituents to a state of better crys-  tallized oxides and to phenomena characteristic of concretion formation. In  the present state of knowledge however, it is not possible to proceed to a  more thorough analysis.  On the basis of the above analysis, even though partial and rather incom-  plete, I will try to structure some pedological processes and to distinguish  some pedogenetic phyla.    295    DETERMINATION   OF  MAIN  PEDOGENETIC  PHYLA  CHARACTERISTIC  OF  THE  SURFACE OF THE EARTH    Certainly, the different processes discussed above for weathering as well as  for "pedogenesis:' never occur alone and in a monotonous manner at a spe-  cific point of the earth surface. As a general rule, however, one of the pheno-  mena prevails. Therefore, the hierarchization of pedologic knowledge can be  performed by refering to the prevailing phenomenon. As for the major crite-  rion that will be used to distinguish each of the great pedologic phyla, I shall  refer to plasma which is actually the central point of pedologic phenomena.  In this perspective, three main phyla may be recognized (Fig. 3).  I    Absence of plasma  formation  (or  imperceptible formation)]  during evolution and  some destruction of preexisting  plasmic   minerals  II    Plasma  formation with plasma-skeleton bonds  persisting    Ill    Plasma  formation and  redistribution due  to  plasma-  skeleton disjunction    Fig. 3. Main pedologic phyla proposed.    Phylum I: Absence of plasma formation (or imperceptible formation) during  evolution and destruction of preexisting plasmic minerals    The pedologic evolution results from the action of a biogeochemical, ag-  gressive and dissolvent weathering that is therefore fully "aplasmogenic" in  the A horizons.  With reference to the three mechanisms described on pp. 290--291, three  major processes may be related to this phylum (Table III).  In all the cases, evolution produces strongly differentiated soils having  prominent horizonation. They can be termed "sols d'alt6ration diff6renci6s"  {soils with differential alteration).    TABLE Ill    Processes of Phylum I    Acidocomplexolysis  Alkalinolysis    Xerolysis -- Ferrolysis    Podzolization (Podzols -- Spodosols)  Solodization (Solods)  (Solodic planosols)  (Auto) planosolization (Planoaols)    296    Phylum H: Plasma formation with remaining plasma--skeleton bonds    Pedological evolution still proceeds from biogeochemical action but leads  here to plasma individualization. Therefore, it is typically "plasmogenic".  According to the nature of plasma, different processes can be observed as  mentioned above. They are listed in Table IV.  In this great phylum of the so-called "sols d'alt6ra