of its nature. For a long time, the type of biogeochemical evolution  (though poorly explained) had priority over transfers into the solid phase  {clay translocation). The latter has been difficult to understand dynamically  and so far, people tended to detect such transfers only from granulometric  data and profile individualization with strong textural differentiation (with-  out microscope observations). Actually, such a way of proceeding is ques-  tionable due to the existing convergence in nature. The discussions indicate,  that strongly differentiated soils may result either from the absence of plas-  ma formation (Phylum I), or from the individualization of a plasma which  will be redistributed afterwards (Phylum III). Therefore, it is necessary to  take into account the predominant mechanisms of pedological evolution, as  proposed in the three major phyla (Table V).    TABLE V    Major pedologic phyla -- their nature and relationships to soil profile morphology    Phylum    Preponderant evolution         Soils  I           Preponderant biogeochemical  evolution without plasma  formation (Aplasmogenic  phylum)    II    III    Preponderant biogeochemical  evolution with plasma  formation and in situ re-  organization (Plasmogenic  phylum with associative pedo-  genesis)    Preponderant textural evolu-  tion due to plasma mobiliza-  tion and redistribution  (Plasmogenic phylum with  dissociative pedogenesis)    Strongly differentiated soils with pro-  eminent horizonation  Sols d'alt~ration diff4renci~s  (Soils with differential alteration)    Sols d'altdration s.s. (geochemically  poorly differentiated)    Soils with textural differentiation  (with gradual transition)    298  APPENDIX I  Major soils units concerned by evolutive processes considered in this study    Soil units:                   Orders:                Classes:  FAO - UNESCO             Soil taxonomy         Classification franqaise,  (1975)                (1975)            CPCS (1967)    (V) Ve